Communism is making a comeback in Russia
Moscow — More than a year ago, during a sabbatical from the American university where I was teaching, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of free speech.
But once upon a time, this place still retained some freedom.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled across the country in an attempt to gain the support of politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Popular protests erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate within the country.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
And the Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
His anti-corruption foundation was banned as "extremist," and its members are being subjected to exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agent" list — or even worse — labeled as "unwanted."
Over the past year, Russia has slipped into a non-free state, although not far away, but very intensely.
For example, a law designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aiming to undermine or discredit institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the extent that even sharing a tweet now serves as a rationale for being labeled a foreign agent.
(Being labeled an "unwelcome person" can result in complete banning.
) This year alone, the foreign agent list has added a record 101 entities.
The cumulative total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above "agents" must be added to the list because they "influence national politics."
But the core objective of journalism and propaganda is obviously to influence politics.
This is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite all this silence and persecution, the only true opposition to the Kremlin has survived and is an unlikely group — the Communist Party.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — encouraging people to support those most likely to defeat candidates supported by the Kremlin — and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data show that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the vote in the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the vote was manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
To many Russians, communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the same communists.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world, but members actually wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some of them are millionaires — such as the charismatic agricultural official Pavel Grudinin, who was barred from participating in last month's elections.
Although the party is still led by 77-year-old Gennadiy Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by young members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
Bondarenko, 36, known by the nickname "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister said Russians should be able to "eat better" on a meager monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko documented his efforts to prove the man wrong on his own YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban from running, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma elections.
Although he was supported by Alexei Navalny's Smart Voting system, he lost to the United Russia candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently created a protest title accusing "the state and government of taking over" United Russia.
Then there is Anastasia Yudashova, 43.
Like Bondarenko, she surprisingly lost the last election.
But she remains — and is becoming even more — popular.
Thanks to the Smart Voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Engalicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reflects a longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the country that aimed to realize these ideals was strict, it was not devoid of justice and compassion.
Furthermore, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which one person's whims do not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" that can stand against Putin's United Russia party.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as the Czech Donald Trump — failed to retain his position as prime minister because the opposition coalition set aside their ideological differences and formed a united alliance, and its leader Petr Fiala is likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition coalition.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also create a unified electoral list for the upcoming parliamentary elections next year and field a single candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, toppling Putin will be much more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party will follow.
But the above practices also pose risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not died," citing the presence of an "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he is at least still interested in pretending not to have led Russia toward something nearly authoritarian.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin imposes and enforces rules as capriciously as it has toward Russian liberals, thereby driving the Communists underground, social explosion becomes more likely.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Russians communists — yes, the communists — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
